is that it is Ka hler. In the mathematical literature, because of
its many special properties, this metric appears in many different
contexts. The metric is asymptotically flat and the complete metric,
, i.e., the self-dual Taub-NUT or Taub-Nut instanton
has the topology of . To avoid confusion due to
divergent conventions in the literature, we will refer to this metric
(and its higher dimensional generalisations to be described in the
next section) as Taub-Nut metrics to distinguish them from the
Taub-Bolt metrics that have two-dimensional regular fixed-point sets
and will reserve the word Taub-NUT for the whole two-parameter family
which includes other regular and singular metrics.
