The Dirichlet Problem: Uniqueness and Non-uniqueness 
In the Dirichlet problem one seeks to obtain non-singular solutions
 which fill in a given boundary
 such that  and
. In our case a boundary is an
 bundle over a compact Einstein manifold with  having
the form
 
where  and  - the radii of the base manifold and the
-fibre respectively - are known quantities and constitute what
we will be referring to as the boundary data. The boundary  is
invariant under the group  where  is the
symmetry group of the base manifold . However,  is not
necessarily the maximal symmetry of . For example when the
boundary is an  bundle over ,  may enlarge from 
 to  depending on the
values of  and  and the periodicity of the
fibre-coordinate. The same is true for the higher dimensional metrics
discussed above.

In the Dirichlet problem we seek to find infilling metrics as
functions of  and . Since we know the Ricci-flat
metrics that have principal orbits sharing the topology and symmetry
of , our problem is equivalent to the isometric embedding
problem of  into known manifolds
. When such an embedding is possible,
compact part(s) of  cut by the
hypersurface  constitute a solution to the Dirichlet
problem.
Schwarzschild Metrics 
For a boundary , the pair
 constitutes the canonical boundary data with the
interpretation that  represents the radius of a spherical
cavity immersed in a thermal bath with temperature 
. It is known from the work of York and others
 that for such canonical boundary data, apart from
the obvious infilling flat-space solution with proper identification,
there are in general two black hole solutions distinguished by their
masses which become degenerate at a certain value of the squashing,
i.e., the ratio of the two radii . This can be
seen in the following way.  First rewrite the Schwarzschild metric
() in the following form:
 
