Rescaling  by , one obtains 
 
where  and . We now obtain a first
order differential equation for  from ():
  
where prime denotes differentiation with respect to . Note that
this equation is inhomogeneous, first order and linear and its
solution is unique for any boundary data 
. More importantly, it is non-autonomous  , unlike the
Einstein equations we started with. This latter property, though not
desirable in most cases, will greatly facilitate our understanding of
the boundary-value problem under consideration.

The apparent singular point  of Eq.( ) is a regular
singular point as one can guess. We will discuss it further when we
deal with the nut-case. For the purpose of exposition we start with
the Bolt case.
Bolt case 
At a bolt, i.e, at  (where ),  is zero trivially as  ( is
nonzero). (The integral  
 
has a factor  for arbitrary , as can be checked by
expanding and factoring the (finite) hypergeometric series making the
squashing zero at the bolt.)

Since  is zero at , Eq.( ) implies
immediately that  and hence  will grow. It will
continue to grow monotonically till it reaches the value where
 - which is an
extremum. The second derivative at the extremum (or at any extremum),
 
is negative. So  starts decreasing and we have a "hump".

Since the second derivative at any extremum is negative for any
 irrespective of the initial data, a minimum can never occur
and hence  will decrease monotonically, i.e.,  will
always be negative after the maximum. This in turn implies that
 can never be negative, i.e., the curve cannot cross the
-axis because that would violate Eq.( ). (This
physically corresponds to the obvious fact that  and
 are positive.)
