Eq.(), which exist only for values of  given by
(), we need not consider  corresponding to values
exceeding the bound of (). Now , as a function of
, increases monotonically from zero (for ) to its maximal
value corresponding to the equality of (). It is
straightforward to check that this maximal value of  is
identically unity. We therefore do not   need to consider the set
of solutions corresponding to  to find the two positive
roots at all. Each of the positive roots of () (and other
roots within this bound) can therefore be given by a single analytic
expression. This is not specific to Eq.(), however, as
 will be equal to unity when the general trinomial equation
