The solutions () and () gives us the masses of the two
infilling black hole solutions as analytic functions of the boundary
data. This enables us to find the corresponding Euclidean actions and
other thermodynamics quantities as analytic functions of the boundary
data and sets the ground for any future study in higher dimensional
black holes in a thermal cavity. Note that, the smaller mass
() will be less than the value of  given by ( )
for which the specific heat capacity
 
is negative and hence the black hole solution is thermodynamically
unstable. The corresponding negative mode was found numerically in
. This solution is therefore an instanton. However, the
larger mass black hole solution is locally thermodynamically
stable. 
